        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Philadelphia&#44; July 18&#44; &#39;90<lb/>
                Rev. Dr. S. Morais.<lb/></p>
            <p>Most Noble Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Being<lb/> aware that the cause of the<lb/> Carmel Colony you have<lb/> near at heart&#44; and that you<lb/> often negotiate with Mr.<lb/> Miller on behalf of the settlers&#44;<lb/> I take the liberty to ask your<lb/> kind intercession in my case<lb/> between me and Mr. Miller.<lb/>  The case in brief is this&#58;<lb/> Last year&#44; June the 13<hi rend="sup">th</hi>&#44; I bought<lb/> of him&#44; Mr. Miller&#44; 103 3<lb/>4 acres<lb/> of land &#40;10&#45;50 &#38; 12 doll. per acre&#41;<lb/> on the following conditions&#58;<lb/> 75 doll. I paid down in cash&#44;<lb/> 125 doll. with interest I had to pay<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the last 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> of September 1889&#59;<lb/> 172 I must pay September 1890&#44;<lb/> and the rest in 6 years&#44; with 6&#37;<lb/> interest.  After a third of the<lb/> whole sum is paid in he is to<lb/> give me a deed and take a<lb/> mortgage on the rest.  In the<lb/> receipt signed by Mr. Miller<lb/> and given me in witness of my<lb/> first payment of 75 doll. &#40;all<lb/> the details of the agreement are<lb/> written&#44; but no provision was<lb/> made to the effect that I lose<lb/> my claims upon the land<lb/> bought in case I be not punctu&#45;<lb/>al in my payments.  To the<lb/> contrary&#44; I was assured that<lb/> Mr. Miller never takes ad&#45;<lb/>vantage of unfavorable circum&#45;<lb/>stances&#44; and never deprives<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>anybody of his land.  Now<lb/> that I was&#44; and still am un&#45;<lb/>able to make the second payment<lb/> of 125 doll.&#44; with interest amounting<lb/> to about &#36;60&#44; or 80&#44; in time&#44; he<lb/> sent me 10 days notice &#40;from<lb/> the 12 to the 22d inst.&#41;&#44; stating that<lb/> in case I do not pay the said<lb/> sum in this short term&#44; he shall<lb/> make sale of my land to other<lb/> parties.  As it is an utter im&#45;<lb/>possibility for me now to comp&#45;<lb/>ly with this demand and in<lb/> the same time I cannot afford<lb/> to lose the land&#44; I turn to your<lb/> kindness Rev. Dr.&#44; asking<lb/> your intercession on my behalf<lb/> before Mr. Miller.  What he can<lb/> and ought to do&#45;&#45;is this&#58; <hi rend="underline">to recall</hi><lb/><hi rend="underline">the notice</hi> served me in regard<lb/> his <sic>intendet</sic> sale of my land&#44; and<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p><hi rend="underline">to wait</hi> a few months longer&#44;<lb/> to the 1st of Feb. next 1891&#44;<lb/> when I hope to be able to meet<lb/> the payments of both &#36;125<lb/> and the &#36;172&#44; as I feel confident<lb/> in the successful sale of the shares<lb/> of the cooperation after the est&#45;<lb/>ablishment of <del>the</del> our first co&#45;<lb/>operative Industry&#45;&#45;the Butter<lb/> and Cheese factory.  I think<lb/> Mr. Miller must understand<lb/> that with the bush land alone<lb/> we cannot solicit a single<lb/> shareholder &#40;of the cooperation&#41;<lb/> while wit ha good industry in<lb/> operation we will be able &#40;to raise<lb/> capital both by earnings and the<lb/> sale of shares.  Having no doubt that<lb/> your letter to Mr. Miller will have<lb/> the desired effect&#44; I beg leave to remain<lb/> with advanced thanks&#44; very Respt. J. Parvin<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="5"/>
            <p><hi rend="underline">P. S.</hi><lb/> Please kindly examine<lb/> into my industrial and educ&#45;<lb/>ational work in Carmel&#44; will<lb/> be very grateful to you for<lb/> your sympathy and moral<lb/> support which would be of<lb/> great value to me.<lb/>  J. P.<lb/></p>
            </body>
